name: Creamy-bellied Antwren
rangeDescription: East slope of andes of peru (huánuco to cusco)
description: Small antwren found in the canopy of foothill forests of the eastern Andes in central Peru. Note the black cap, striped face, white wingbars, and lack of rufous in the wing.

name: White-headed Vulture
rangeDescription: Thornscrub and desert of sub-saharan africa
description: A medium-sized, mostly dark vulture with an angular, naked, pale pink head and bulky coral-colored beak. In flight, the adult’s white “armpits” extend out as a stripe along the middle of the underwing; the larger females differ from males by having all-white innermost flight feathers.

name: Crested Eagle
rangeDescription: Forest of eastern guatemala to northeastern argentina and southern brazil
description: A huge, rare eagle, found in large swaths of mature lowland and foothill forests through much of Central and South America. Always rare and infrequently seen; any day with a Crested Eagle deserves a gold star.

name: See-see Partridge
rangeDescription: Dry foothills and plateaus of southeastern turkey, northern syria, and (locally) northern saudi arabia to southern armenia, uzbekistan, southeastern turkmenistan, southern tajikistan southward through iran and afghanistan (except northeastern), to sub-himalayan pakistan
description: Eye-catching small gamebird of barren hills and wadis in arid and semi-arid areas. Note male’s black eyebrow, white ear patch, bright orange bill, and contrasting striped flanks.

name: White-rumped Cuckooshrike
rangeDescription: Lowlands of sulawesi and adjacent islands
description: A chunky bird with a thick bill, a gray body, a black face, a beady eye, and a white belly and rump that contrast with a black tail. Paler juvenile shows barring on underside.

name: Pinyon Jay
rangeDescription: Pinyon-juniper woodland of southern oregon to southwestern usa and northern baja california
description: This jay has a dusty-looking blue body and a brighter cerulean face. Shorter tail and longer, more sharply pointed bill than other jays.

name: Giant Weaver
description: A spectacular enormous weaver endemic to São Tomé, with a robust barbet-like bill and a bulky head. Adult male has a black head and a chestnut collar that extends to the breast.
imageCreditName: Lars Petersson | My World of Bird Photography

name: Pearly-bellied Seedeater
rangeDescription: Eastern paraguay to southern brazil (southern mato grosso) and northeastern argentina
description: Very small finchlike bird with a short bill. Inhabits savannas and grasslands, where it often joins flocks of other seedeater species.

name: Green-bearded Helmetcrest
rangeDescription: Páramo of eastern andes of colombia (south to cundinamarca)
description: This stunning hummingbird is distinctive within its limited range in north-central Colombia. Males have a pointed green strip on the throat bordered by white and a spiky black-and-white crest.

name: Thick-billed Seed-Finch
rangeDescription: Southern mexico (veracruz) to western colombia and western ecuador; also coiba and pearl islands
description: Small seed-eating bird of humid tropical lowlands; uncommon. Found in damp grassy areas, overgrown weedy fields, and forest edges, often in areas with scattered bushes and small trees.
